Here are both approaches for Shell navigation in .NET MAUI:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string vs. complex object:**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs (source)
[RelayCommand]
async Task OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass the ID as a query string
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass the full object via a dictionary
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs (target)
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    string productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // fetch full product from a service, etc.
        }

        // Approach B: full object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | Dictionary object |
|---|---|---|
| **GoToAsync** | interpolated URI | URI + `Dictionary<string, object>` |
| **Received as** | `string` (boxed as `object`) | original `Product` reference |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ yes | ❌ no (in-process only) |
| **Serialization** | none needed | none needed (passed by ref) |

Use **string parameters** when the value is simple or you need deep-link / URI support. Use the **dictionary overload** when you need to pass complex objects without serialization.
